Gorguts and Necrophagists are great yin and yangs. The disso and the melodic takes of a genre wishing to push past its previous boundaries, both seeking that in completely opposite directions. For that melodic approach I think that First Fragment is shred tech death in an almost finalized ideal, maybe I'm wrong, but I have no idea how someone is going to make something better in that style.

posts.com: If, on the other hand, we estimate the worth of the Beautiful Arts by the culture they supply to the mind, and take as a standard the expansion of the faculties which must concur in the Judgement for cognition, Music will have the lowest place among them (as it has perhaps the highest among those arts which are valued for their pleasantness), because it merely plays with sensations. The formative arts are far before it in this point of view; for in putting the Imagination in a free play, which is also accordant with the Understanding, they at the same time carry on a serious business. This they do by producing a product that serves for concepts as a permanent self-commendatory vehicle for promoting their union with sensibility and thus, as it were, the urbanity of the higher cognitive powers. These two species of art take quite different courses; the first proceeds from sensations to indeterminate Ideas, the second from determinate Ideas to sensations. The latter produce permanent, the former only transitory impressions. The Imagination can recall the one and entertain itself pleasantly therewith; but the other either vanish entirely, or if they are recalled involuntarily by the Imagination they are rather wearisome than pleasant. Besides, there attaches to Music a certain want of urbanity from the fact that, chiefly from the character of its instruments, it extends its influence further than is desired (in the neighbourhood), and so as it were obtrudes itself, and does violence to the freedom of others who are not of the musical company. The Arts which appeal to the eyes do not do this; for we need only turn our eyes away, if we wish to avoid being impressed. The case of music is almost like that of the delight derived from a smell that diffuses itself widely. The man who pulls his perfumed handkerchief out of his pocket attracts the attention of all round him, even against their will, and he forces them, if they are to breathe at all, to enjoy the scent;

It's important to realize that we only really know him for the end of his career - that is with the NBC Orchestra and those late 30s-early 50s recordings. He was more critically acclaimed for his tenure with the New York Philharmonic, of which we have far fewer recordings (and the few that we do have are in pretty bad sound). The recordings that are in listenable shape reveal a more flexible conductor, especially outside of classical-era repertoire.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114102256
>best amp sim for guitar and/or bass? maybe i'm just retarded but i can't get a good tone out of logic's default ones.
I have used Logic's amps and I found that for a hard rock/metal tone, I needed to do a couple of EQ moves. I think I did this.
1. High shelf boost before the amp.
2. Pretty big mid-scoop after the amp.
3. Pretty big bass boost around 70-100hz, depending on your tuning.
4. High-cut the really bright frequencies, at least above 10k, but possibly even lower than that.
5. You might want a boost around 6k for brightness.
6. Precise notch cuts to dampen resonant frequencies.

Remember that amp sims are really just algorithmic distortion and filters in a box. You can usually get a good tone out of anything with conscious EQ moves.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114125247
I remember the built-in tutorials being decent in 2012. They're probably at least as good now. Sorry I don't have more current info, but here are some very important hotkeys for starters:

>"Tab" switches between horizontal (arrangement) and vertical (session) views
>"Tab" + "Shift" switches between effects view on the bottom and edit view for the selected clip

Also, you'll want to download/install ASIO4ALL if you're on a PC, then set it as your audio driver in the settings menu. It'll help get you lower latency than default Windows drivers.

Last thing - learn where the "record arm" buttons are if you wanna record stuff. In the vertical view, you can click the little record circles for each clip space. If you wanna record to the main timeline, press F9 or click the record button up top. Good luck anon

>>114102823
Listened to the whole album
That beat drop on track 4 was really good, wasnt expecting that. Those drums and synthd make me think of Orchestral Manouevres at the Dark. Maybe my favorite part of this EP
Vocals are a bit buried in all tracks. Nice bass on track 2. Track 1 isnt really a strong opener to the album I think.
Something about the tracks overall make me not really get into the vibe of the album and engage with it completely. It seems a bit monotonous maybe, like the album is just going through the motions and no part is really different than another. For example, track 2 has a synth solo but when it hapoens everything else (bass, guitar, back synth, drums especially) is just doing the same thing they were already doing. That can be me not being familiar with the style, but I feel the tracks would be better with something to grab the listener. Maybe develop the ideas you have in the arrangement a bit, what I get from it is no moment really standing out. It could help giving some relief (in the architectural sense). Track 3 for example is a bit better in this regard, but even with some cool different synth stuff being introduced the rest of it is still is very much of the same and the vocals being buried doesnt help.
Anyway I like the elements here I just think they could fit together in a better way. Im also not a huge fan of the vague/suggestive lyrics
The final track is a good album closer, maybe the guitar could let itself go a bit tho and play around the synth. But the guitar notes complement the synths really well here

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114141061
Well first off don't spend money on something that you can get on rutracker for free. Or do. Either way get the producer edition.

>All I know is "teehee this sounds good to my ears"
You'll unironically be more interesting than most musicians who start from a base of music theory which is a good thing if you want to make what you like. If you want to make a career of this then you should learn theory but if that's not your goal then you should absolutely go in and learn by doing. When it comes to sound design, while you do need to eventually understand a lot of technical stuff, the best way to do that is to just get in and fiddle with shit. Load up a synth and everytime you encounter a setting that you don't understand, Google it and learn that way. I watched this video when I started and it helped a lot despite its age, its all still fundamentally the same stuff and once you have the basics down you can expand into the newer styles of synthesis much much easier https://youtu.be/atvtBE6t48M

You're going to make great stuff anon, I can tell by your attitude and desire to learn. I wish you all the best.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114141324
I should add that when I first started fucking around, the idea that I'd be able to look at a synth and know what everything does was insane to me, completely unbelievable. I'd stay up crazy late, putting in so much effort and feeling like shit because what I made just sucked and I expected to never be able to create something I'd really like. Now, while I have literally 0 commercial success whatsoever (which is kind of nice because it makes me feel like a secret) I do really enjoy what I make even if it is still cringe worthy and wouldn't even be considered music by most respectable people. I'd never have gotten to this point of self satisfaction if I wasn't constantly messing around with shit I didn't understand until I understood it.

It's also worth noting that you will likely never feel completely satisfied with your art which is not only a good thing but the case for everyone. So don't worry about it being hard to learn or get discouraged by not knowing much right now, if a retard like me can learn this shit then you absolutely can.

>>114141388
Doesn't really matter, what's more important is synthesis types. Learn subtractive synthesis first, then additive and then fm. Once you understand those you can branch out into wavetables, granular and physical modelling if you're into that. Subtractive and fm are the absolute core to know and fm is much easier to learn when you understand subtractive so learn subtractive synthesis. What daw are you using? Fl studio? And if so what version, producer, signature etc

>In 1848 the 29-year-old Ruskin – two volumes of the influential Modern Painters to his name and at work on The Seven Lamps of Architecture – married Euphemia Gray, the beautiful 19-year-old daughter of family friends. After six increasingly unhappy years, Effie fell in love with her husband's protege Millais and set about having the marriage annulled.

>What reverberated then and now was that the reason given for ending the union was non-consummation. But what really snagged in the public consciousness was Ruskin's explanation of why he didn't fulfil his marital duties: "It may be thought strange that I could abstain from a woman who to most people was so attractive. But though her face was beautiful, her person was not formed to excite passion. On the contrary, there were certain circumstances in her person which completely checked it."

>Those "certain circumstances" have been the cause of much salacious speculation. The reasons mooted range from his aversion to children, his religious scruples, a wish to preserve Effie's beauty and to keep her from exhaustion so they could go Alpine walking, to a revulsion with body odour and menstruation. Effie herself was the inadvertent source of the most famous of explanations: Ruskin, she said, "had imagined women were quite different to what he saw I was, and that the reason he did not make me his Wife was because he was disgusted with my person the first evening". From this emerged the canard that Ruskin, used only to the smoothness of classical statues of the nude, was repulsed by the wedding-night revelation that Effie had pubic hair. It may not rival Cleopatra's nose, but poor Effie has gone down as the possessor of the most famous genital coiffure in history.

Foxtrot and Selling England by the Pound are equally proggy but also very theatrical, incorporating elements of genres like music hall. That description may sound similar to Lamb Lies Down, but they focus on British storytelling like their earlier albums and the folk sound is still there

From Genesis to Revelation is Moody Blues-inspired folkpop
Trespass and Nursery Cryme are where they get more proggy but still within the folk realm. A lot more somber in my opinion. Wonderful storytelling. Their most underrated stuff
Foxtrot and Selling England By The Pound is still similar to their other stuff but a lot more theatric (using elements of music hall for example), their classical music inspiration being a lot more upfront as well, and more rock-oriented (psychedelic rock and of course progressive rock), but still within their British folk roots as far as overall sound and storytelling/lyricism goes. This is the fan favorite era.

>"emo" is definitely in the running for most vague and misused genre term. how can it describe rites of spring, american football, and mcr simultaneously?
Here's what I know

Well for starters it really depends WHERE and WHEN this conversation is being held. If we were in the 80s and on the East Coast, we wouldn't even use the word "emo", we'd just view it as Hardcore/Post Hardcore. Also as far as I know, all these terms were made in "retrospect", which makes since a lot of older iconic "Emo bands" reject the term and always talk about how they were never emo, just some offshoot of Hardcore shit or just Indie stuff lol. If you're interested you should look into the Revolution Summer of 85 where Hardcore bands wanted to get sad and stuff.

Also Emo originally stood for Emocore which stood for Emotional Hardcore.

Midwest Emo is just a mix mash of Indie shit with the harsher sounds of Hardcore to create a beautiful genre of noise and bliss. This is probably the first time where there's a "variant" of what is ME, like you simultaneously have bands doing shit like American Football which is just sonic bliss but also bands like Mineral who while I love, feel more faithful to Emocore with light splashes of Indie tunes.

The problem with MCR is that Emo got a bad rap, looking into Emo War (unironically a real thing), basically Emo was portrayed by mainstream media to be all down and depressing and like all outsider groups or cultures, was very odd and weird. but if you know most about Emo, there's a really stark difference between anything before 2000s and after. MCR were never emo, with even Gerard denouncing emo as a genre and their band as an Emo band. Some people call it Mall Emo, some people see it as Fake Emo, some see it as pop punk.

You may not know this, but the widely popular song "Revolution 1" from the Beatles' White Album was copied from Mike Love's "Student Demonstration Time".
Mike Love traveled to India with the Beatles in 1968, where he played them his song, which was really appreciated by John Lennon.
Unfortunately, the Beatles ripped him off by releasing "Revolution 1" in the same year, and never gave him credit for it.
Mike is also the original author of "Back in the USSR", which came from him playing "California Girls" to the Beatles during their trip to India. He was once again ripped off, with this song being the opener for the White Album.
Mike Love is one of the most important artists of the 20th century, pioneering many different music genres.
His 1970 song "All I Wanna Do", for instance, is widely regarded as the first dream pop track. Mike was ahead of his time, while Brian Wilson called that song boring.
Most of the Beach Boys' greatest songs were actually written by Mike Love, although Brian Wilson tried to hide this fact by falsely claiming they he had written them on his own. Mike had to sue Wilson in order to be recognized for his creative work.
In conclusion, while most people worship this talentless schizo known as Brian Wilson, the few connoisseurs who actually understand a thing or two about music will recognize the talent of Mike Love, the true genius of the Beach Boys.

>>114139020
Yes visualizing patterns will help but chords are about understanding the relationship between the notes. Triads are the most basic chords. If you know the function of the notes then you can manipulate them to make new chords & voicings. For example a major chord is the Root 3rd and 5th notes of the major scale as shown in the pic. Minor chords are the similar but one note different with the Root *flat 3rd* and 5th.

The goal is to be able to put your finger down on any one root note on the thinnest three strings, and be able to form a major or minor triad around it.

I also know nothing about electricity. The hardest part is finding a wiring diagram for off spec wiring. I like to use unleaded silver bearing solder with rosin core because that shit flows real nice. I'd also recommend a KSGER soldering station off Amazon if you're serious about guitar building. They're about 75$. Pic related is going to be going into a Plywood Kramer Striker body with a Japanese ESP made Kramer Focus neck. She's gonna have an EVH Wolfgang in the bridge slanted with some GFS Alnico II single coils and a 250k Bourns pot. Really excited to try that pickup combo together no tone 1 volume.

Don't expect to just bolt everything together. Even with these old Asian Kramers. There's a LOT of redrilling, measuring, making sure the scale is right, making sure the bridge posts line up, making sure you have the right size locking nut (modern R2/R3/R4 are a few millimeters taller than vintage ones), etc. But you can make some wicked cool shit. Try starting out on some cheap kit guitars. Learn fret leveling, basic soldering, etc. If you fuck up, you're not out a lot of money.

You're doing fine. Like everyone else said, focus on doing it right rather than making it sound right. There will be a lot of opportunities for shortcuts that make bad habits. Once you get your footing and you can stumble through a song or two, start playing along with the track AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. You will not be able to play songs with any degree of proficiency unless you practice with the track. I was a total retard who didn't do this for the first year I practiced which basically meant I learned some chords but didn't know how to actually play anything.

Stick with it, you're going to feel like you're the worst player ever for a long time. Always be working on something that's slightly above your skill level. Take lessons if you have the cash and can find a good teacher.
